I just bought a new pair of running shoes, from Brooks Running.

I've been suffering from plantar fasciitis for several months, and needed something soft that would allow me to train on the road without exacerbating the symptoms.

This is, of course, profoundly uninteresting.

But what is interesting is the product video that sealed the deal for me.

https://lnkd.in/eW7ScyXH

It's incredibly simple. Just a product expert speaking for 1 minute, holding the product.

2 Cameras. Shot in the office. Tight script (probably) into a teleprompter.

Can't have taken more than 20 minutes to film, less than an hour to edit.

And it works extremely well to increase conversion rate.

Why? It fosters a human-to-human connection between the producer and customer, which builds trust. 

Through this video, I am gaining a better understanding of the people who created the product and what they are proud of.

The thing that makes it good:
- Real person
- Genuine expertise
- Clear value proposition

Yet, if you try to make this with AI, it's instantly awful. It doesn't matter how good avatars get - the moment you lose authenticity, you lose value.

Nothing is as infectious as enthusiastic experts.

AI is coming for a lot of things, but it isn't coming for this

